One thing you're on the right track with: you're considering some of the most nimble & acrobatic animals that might best adapt to zero-G. A little on the small-frame side is another plus; lower mass is easier to manage in zero-G. Less momentum takes less energy to control & maneuver, less chance of injury by uncontrolled collisions with objects, people, walls, etc.

With those considerations, what job(s) would they be fulfilling? Techs/mechanics who are assembling space living/manufacturing facilities, for example.

No need to choose just one species. Cats are always cool & familiar, but doesn't mean there aren't otters swimming around and teasing them, too. How are they designed? How did they come into existence? Are they evolved beings in natural form? Are they genetically engineered by humans or other species specifically as helper/specialized workers?

Personally, I'm really partial to cats. A bobcat, ocelot, lynx, cheetah waifur would be my strong preference, given a choice. Maybe a genetically engineered mix of several of the cats rather than a more pure strain of one particular species. But I'm open-minded and would consider a number of others. Important to me would be intellectual capacity on a ship or station. Maybe I'm a science researcher orbiting Jupiter and my waifur is a peer in another research specialty. Or a highly skilled tech helping to build/manufacture/maintain the environment.

On a small station with two or three dozen total inhabitants, sex & cuddles would be essential for a ten or 20 year assignment. But, I'd also want to be able to play every board game ever invented with her, too, along with other intellectual engagement. Zero- or low-G martial arts would be awesome with a waifur as sparring partner.

But I do agree that the idea of future prosthetics just being a straight up upgrade really hampers on the loss of losing a limb, and we intend to make that sort of perfection thing a far off goal that she wants to get, but it's far, far out of reach for her.

>impossible to be objective, it is the opinion of one guy
